title: 5 things I learned from the Arizona State vs. Utah game
text:
5 things I learned from the Arizona State vs. Utah game Carra McManamon, KSL.com Contributor | 
1. It's not how you start it's how you finish 
A slow Utah start kept Arizona State in the game until the fourth quarter Saturday night. Arizona State seemed to have an answer for everything Utah did. Utah went into halftime with a 14-10 lead, but Arizona State got the ball to open the second half. After four punts between both teams, Arizona State kicked a field goal and then scored a safety on a bizarre play by Utah's special teams unit. Things seemed to be working in Arizona State's favor. 
2. When Travis Wilson is on he's on 
Arizona State brought a lot of pressure, and with how well Devontae Booker has been playing it was no surprise Utah needed Wilson to bring one of his better passing games. Wilson was 26-of-36 on the night for 297 yards and two touchdowns. Wilson looked confident in his receivers. Kenneth Scott had a career-high 166 receiving yards.
